<DOC><DOCNO> AP891122-0143 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-22-89 1800EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-HolidaySurvey     11-22 0406</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Holiday Survey,0417</SECOND><HEAD>97 Percent Head Home For Holidays</HEAD><HEAD>With AM-Thanksgiving-Hugo Bjt</HEAD><DATELINE>ORRVILLE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   There's no place like home for theholidays for most Americans, according to a poll released Wednesday.   Ninety-seven percent of Americans surveyed spend one or moreholidays with their families each year, according to poll conductedfor the J.M. Smucker Co.   The survey also showed the respondents were more likely thanusual to say grace before eating their holiday meal.   ``We are pleased with the survey's results, which seem toindicate that Old-World values are still alive and well in theU.S.,'' said Tim Smucker, chairman of the Orrville-based jelly andjam maker.   According to the survey, Christmas and Thanksgiving were themost popular holidays for gathering with relatives, with 95 percentof those surveyed spending at least Christmas or Thanksgiving withfamily members.   Participants were asked if they usually celebrate any of sixholidays with family: New Year's, Valentine's Day, Easter, MemorialDay, July Fourth, Labor Day, Thanksgiving and Christmas.   Eighty-three percent of those surveyed begin their holiday mealswith a prayer or grace, while 48 percent begin daily meals that way.   Respondents from all regions said they were likely to say graceor a prayer before a holiday meal. Ninety percent of respondents inthe South, 86 percent of those polled in the Midwest, 77 percent ofthose in the Northeast and 72 percent of the respondents in theWest said they planned to give thanks before holiday dining.   People surveyed in the South were the most likely to reportbeginning everyday meals with grace. Fifty-eight percent ofSoutherners polled said they started daily meals with a prayer,while 39 percent of the respondents in both the Northeast and Westsaid they did so.   Asked which values they want most for their children to learn,58 percent of those polled said honesty, 48 percent said a beliefin God and 27 percent said a respect for elders.   The telephone poll of 1,030 adults nationwide was conducted Nov.3-5 by Bruskin Associates of New Brunswick, N.J. The poll had amargin of error of plus or minus 3 percentage points.   The director of the survey, Dick Bruskin, said the surveyresults were a change of pace.   ``We're so used to dealing with statistics that point to thedeterioration of family life that this study comes as encouragingnews about where the American family really is today,'' he said.</TEXT></DOC>